<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="156" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1509,2038]" pageId="3" pageNumber="156">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1617,1642]" pageId="3" pageNumber="156">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species has been recorded from Southeastern and Southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1107,1178,1617,1642]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="156">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, and this is the third municipality record from the State of São Paulo (
<bibRefCitation author="Moreira" box="[718,1009,1653,1678]" pageId="3" pageNumber="156" refString="Moreira, F. F. F. &amp; Barbosa, J. F. (2011) The Veliidae (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Gerromorpha) from Sao Paulo State, Brazil: new species, description of the male of Microvelia ioana Drake &amp; Hottes, 1952, and synonymical and distributional notes. Annales de Limnologie, 47, 297 - 311. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1051 / limn / 2011010" type="journal article" year="2011">
Moreira &amp; Barbosa 
<number box="[951,1009,1654,1678]" pageId="3" pageNumber="156" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigues" box="[1023,1276,1653,1678]" pageId="3" pageNumber="156" refString="Rodrigues, H. D. D., Melo, A. L. &amp; Ferreira-Keppler, R. L. (2014) Taxonomic revision of the Neotropical genus Oiovelia (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Veliidae). Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae, 54 (1), 65 - 98." type="journal article" year="2014">
Rodrigues 
<emphasis box="[1147,1199,1653,1677]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="156">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[1215,1276,1654,1678]" pageId="3" pageNumber="156" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Through the examination of the recently collected specimens, intraspecific variation in body length and particular morphological structures was observed. Body lengths measured 
<quantity box="[895,1062,1725,1750]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" metricValueMax="3.75" metricValueMin="2.85" pageId="3" pageNumber="156" unit="mm" value="3.3" valueMax="3.75" valueMin="2.85">2.85–3.75 mm</quantity>
(macropterous male), 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.45" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="3.4" pageId="3" pageNumber="156" unit="mm" value="3.45" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="3.4">3.40–3.50 mm</quantity>
(apterous male), and 
<quantity box="[441,542,1762,1786]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="3" pageNumber="156" unit="mm" value="3.2">3.20 mm</quantity>
(macropterous female), some of which were smaller or greater than mentioned in the literature.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1509,2038]" pageId="3" pageNumber="156">
Most of the specimens have the margins of the pronotum, abdomen, and legs with several long setae (
<figureCitation box="[1340,1422,1833,1858]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1281,1304]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,200,1253]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[156,1431,193,1260]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 17. Species of Oiovelia, dorsal habitus. 12 – 14. Oiovelia brasiliensis Moreira et al., 2010 (Brazil, São Paulo State, Paranapiacaba); 12. apterous female. 13. macropterous male; 14. macropterous female; 15. Oiovelia cunucunumana Drake &amp; Maldonado-Capriles, 1952 (Brazil, Bahia State); 16 – 17. Oiovelia viannai Rodrigues &amp; Melo, 2014; 16. apterous female (Brazil, Bahia State); 17. macropterous female (paratype MZUSP)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264969/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="156">
Fig. 
<number box="[1392,1422,1834,1858]" pageId="3" pageNumber="156" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
), but some have fewer setae along the body (
<figureCitation box="[641,726,1869,1894]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1281,1304]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,200,1253]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[156,1431,193,1260]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 17. Species of Oiovelia, dorsal habitus. 12 – 14. Oiovelia brasiliensis Moreira et al., 2010 (Brazil, São Paulo State, Paranapiacaba); 12. apterous female. 13. macropterous male; 14. macropterous female; 15. Oiovelia cunucunumana Drake &amp; Maldonado-Capriles, 1952 (Brazil, Bahia State); 16 – 17. Oiovelia viannai Rodrigues &amp; Melo, 2014; 16. apterous female (Brazil, Bahia State); 17. macropterous female (paratype MZUSP)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264969/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="156">
Fig. 
<number box="[695,726,1870,1894]" pageId="3" pageNumber="156" value="14.0">14</number>
</figureCitation>
). The pruinose area on the posterior lobe of the pronotum may be evident (
<figureCitation box="[282,363,1905,1930]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1281,1304]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,200,1253]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[156,1431,193,1260]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 17. Species of Oiovelia, dorsal habitus. 12 – 14. Oiovelia brasiliensis Moreira et al., 2010 (Brazil, São Paulo State, Paranapiacaba); 12. apterous female. 13. macropterous male; 14. macropterous female; 15. Oiovelia cunucunumana Drake &amp; Maldonado-Capriles, 1952 (Brazil, Bahia State); 16 – 17. Oiovelia viannai Rodrigues &amp; Melo, 2014; 16. apterous female (Brazil, Bahia State); 17. macropterous female (paratype MZUSP)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264969/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="156">
Fig. 
<number box="[334,363,1906,1930]" pageId="3" pageNumber="156" value="14.0">14</number>
</figureCitation>
) or not (
<figureCitation box="[460,542,1905,1930]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1281,1304]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,200,1253]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[156,1431,193,1260]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 17. Species of Oiovelia, dorsal habitus. 12 – 14. Oiovelia brasiliensis Moreira et al., 2010 (Brazil, São Paulo State, Paranapiacaba); 12. apterous female. 13. macropterous male; 14. macropterous female; 15. Oiovelia cunucunumana Drake &amp; Maldonado-Capriles, 1952 (Brazil, Bahia State); 16 – 17. Oiovelia viannai Rodrigues &amp; Melo, 2014; 16. apterous female (Brazil, Bahia State); 17. macropterous female (paratype MZUSP)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/264969/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="156">
Fig. 
<number box="[512,542,1906,1930]" pageId="3" pageNumber="156" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
), and the slight constriction on abdominal sternites III–IV of the female is more developed in the macropterous form, whereas some apterous females do not show this condition. Finally, a few specimens have the upper portion of the abdominal segments orange and the region below the points of insertion of lateral abdominal muscles dark brown to blackish.
</paragraph>
